article.headline: Monarchs stay hot, but 3-15 start cools future
article.linkText: Monarchs' sixth straight win a little too late
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The Sacramento Monarchs are on the
longest winning streak in franchise history. Trouble is, it's about
five weeks too late.

	   Ruthie Bolton scored 14 of her 20 points after halftime, and
Yolanda Griffith had 19 points Thursday night as the Monarchs won
their sixth straight, beating the playoff-bound Utah Starzz 80-71.

	   Sacramento, a Western Conference finalist last season, has been
playing up to its standards recently with eight victories in its
last 10 games, including the longest winning streak in the
respectable franchise history of a three-time playoff team.

	   But the Monarchs' 3-15 start, caused by prolonged stretches on
the injured list for Griffith and All-Star Ticha Penicheiro, doomed
their season more than a month ago.

	   "I'm very proud of this team because we've never given up or
had bad attitudes,'' Sacramento coach Maura McHugh said. "This is
fun. I like seeing this team challenge anyone who comes their
way.''

	   The Monarchs blew a 15-point lead in the second half, but
Griffith and Tangela Smith, who had 19 points and 12 rebounds, led
a late rally for the Monarchs, who went 23-for-24 on free throws.
Sacramento made an 11-3 run in the final 1:07, highlighted by six
points from Smith.

	   Griffith and Smith led the Monarchs' defensive effort against
Margo Dydek, the Starzz's 7-foot-2 Polish center who matched her
career high with 27 points. Dydek was relentless in the second
half, scoring 23 points, until the Monarchs disrupted her
deliberate low-post game.

	   "It's tough down there every night, but we fought back and
pulled together,'' Griffith said. "Six wins are great, but we're
not thinking about that right now. We just want to finish at
.500.''

	   To do that, Sacramento (10-16) must win its final six games,
starting with a Saturday visit from defending champion Los Angeles.

	   Though Sacramento almost certainly won't make the playoffs, the
Monarchs prevented Utah (18-9) from clinching a playoff berth.

	   Dydek also grabbed 11 rebounds for the Starzz, who lost for just
the third time in 11 games. Adrienne Goodson added 14 points and
eight rebounds for the Starzz, who got just seven points from
Olympian Natalie Williams before she fouled out.

	   The Starzz appeared a bit tired from a game Wednesday night
against Miami.

	   "We could have easily come out and been blown out of this
building,'' Utah coach Candi Harvey said. "I thought that this was
the Sacramento team of old. It seems they're playing great
basketball right now.''

	   Utah shot 30 percent in the first half, and Sacramento went up
39-24 on Lady Grooms' layup 33 seconds after halftime. But the
Starzz chipped away while the Monarchs went cold, making a 17-4 run
-- with 12 of the points from Dydek, who bulled over Griffith
repeatedly -- in the next 5½ minutes.

	   Seldom-used guard Elisa Aguilar hit two 3-pointers as Utah went
up by six in the second half, but the Monarchs tied it with 3½
minutes left. Griffith's three-point play with 1:07 remaining gave
Sacramento a 72-68 lead, and Smith hit a jumper and four free
throws to seal it.
